GT_Text.Value: Altered Striatal Dopamine D2 Receptor Density and Dopamine Transport in a Patient with Hepatic Encephalopathy
Altered Striatal Dopamine D2 Receptor Density and
Dopamine Transport in a Patient with Hepatic
Karin Weissenborn ' 4, Georg Berding 2, and Herbert Kostler 3
Karin Weissenborn ' 4, Georg Berding 2, and Herbert Kostler 3

A patient suffering from liver cirrhosis presented with a bradykinetic-rigid syndrome suspected as Parkinson's disease. A detailed work-up of the case revealed hepatic encephalopathy as the cause of the neurological symptomatology. An alteration of striatal dopamine D, receptor binding and dopamine re-uptake sites was demonstrated by 1211-iodobenzamide (IBZM) and '2'1-P-CIT single photon emission computed tomography (SPECT), respectively. It is suggested that the alteration of the dopamine re-uptake in cirrhotics may be the cause of an increased catabolism of dopamine in HE.
